WHO   — THE EUPHEMISM TREADMILL — a PHONETIKOS entry
WHAT  — THE EUPHEMISM TREADMILL — Pinker's name for the loop by which polite words keep going bad, because changing the word never changes the feeling underneath it.
WHERE — wherever a culture is squeamish about a referent — death, the body, disability, race  Framework inputs: Steven Pinker, The Blank Slate (2002); the literature on semantic pejoration; Allan & Burridge, Forbidden Words  Conductor / external anchor: ROOT0 (catalogued into UD0)
WHY   — because the stigma lives in the attitude toward the referent, not in the label — so it reattaches to whatever word you choose next.
HOW   — a euphemism absorbs the connotations of the thing it names, decays into the very taboo it was meant to soften, and is replaced by a fresh euphemism, on a loop.

awareness — what the node knows of itself:
  The word was never the wound; change the word and the wound renames it.

